true" display="localdateshort" UTC="true">20081030T18:00:00</Date><Author type="string" label="Author's Name" readonly="false" hidden="false" required="true">Brian Schmidt</Author><BodyCopy type="dhtml" label="Body Copy" readonly="false" hidden="false" required="false" Height=""><![CDATA[<div style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; background-color: #ffffff; color: #000000; line-height: normal;">Principle Four of the Learning Model states that &ldquo;learners and teachers at BYU-Idaho act for themselves and accept responsibility for learning and teaching.&rdquo;
<p><br />Learning by faith does not come without effort and sacrifice. Teachers and students are expected to act in accordance with their faith in the Lord Jesus Christ; these actions include diligent effort and preparation, participation, reflection and prayer, and maintaining a proper attitude toward learning. When learners and teachers exercise agency by acting in accordance with correct principles, they open their hearts to the Holy Ghost and invite His teaching.</p>
<p>This summer several faculty members accepted an invitation to be interviewed on camera regarding their thoughts and experiences with the Learning Model. This story features segments of these interviews relating to agency, responsibility, and the exercise of faith in the classroom. While not intended to cover the principle of &ldquo;act for themselves&rdquo; in a comprehensive fashion, these faculty insights might spark ideas and thoughts. A brief quotation highlights each faculty member&rsquo;s comments. To watch the video segment, click on the quotation or the picture.</p>
<p><br />We invite you to add your own thoughts and experiences by logging in below.</p>
